ange from <i>-er-</i> to <i>-ar-</i> was a characteristic phonetic development in Middle English.)"]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":14,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Alexander Parkinson was born about 1368, his father, John le Perkinson, was 36 and his mother, Margaret Placedieu, was 24. He had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with Betty Bowers. He died in 1417, in Lancashire, England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"about 1368–1417":"umbes 1368–1417","1368–1417":"1368–1417","1385–Female":"1385–Surnud","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1412–Male":"1412–Surnud","1415–1490":"1415–1490","1417–1471":"1417–1471","1334–Male":"1334–Surnud","1345–1374":"1345–1374","before 1368":"enne 1368","1374":"1374","1385":"1385","1471":"1471","1382":"1382","1490":"1490","1415":"1415","1412":"1412","1368":"1368","1345":"1345","1334":"1334